SIMPLE: scruple
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scruple
<hw>Scru"ple</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>scrupulus</ets> a small sharp or pointed stone, the twenty-fourth
part of an ounce, a scruple, uneasiness, doubt, dim. of
<ets>scrupus</ets> a rough or sharp stone, anxiety, uneasiness; perh.
akin to Gr. <?/ the chippings of stone, <?/ a razor, Skr.
<ets>kshura</ets>: cf. F. <ets>scrupule</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
weight of twenty grains; the third part of a dram.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, a very small quantity; a particle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will not bate thee a <qex>scruple</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Hesitation as to action from the difficulty of
determining what is right or expedient; unwillingness, doubt, or
hesitation proceeding from motives of conscience.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He was made miserable by the conflict between his tastes and his
<qex>scruples</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To make scruple</b></col>, <cd>to hesitate from
conscientious motives; to scruple.</cd> <qau>Locke.</qau></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scruple</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Scruple
<hw>Scru"ple</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Scrupled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Scrupling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To be reluctant or
to hesitate, as regards an action, on account of considerations of
conscience or expedience.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We are often over-precise, scrupling to say or do those things
which lawfully we may.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men <qex>scruple</qex> at the lawfulness of a set form of divine
worship.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scruple</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Scruple
<hw>Scru"ple</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To regard with
suspicion; to hesitate at; to question.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Others long before them . . . <qex>scrupled</qex> more the books
of heretics than of gentiles.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To excite scruples in; to cause to scruple.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Letters which did still <qex>scruple</qex> many of them.</q>
<rj><qau>E. Symmons.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scrupler</ent>⟦br⟧
